      <hedline>
        <hl1>France's Agenda in Zaire Only Harms Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher Albin-Lackey letter on David Aronson's Mar 18 article on France's policy in Zaire (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Aronson, in ''Zaire's French Connection''(Op-Ed, March 18), is right to call attention to the self-serving nature of France's foreign policy in West Africa.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Aronson, in ''Zaire's French Connection''(Op-Ed, March 18), is right to call attention to the self-serving nature of France's foreign policy in West Africa.</p>
        <p>I recently spent five months in a study program in Niger, a country in which a democratic Government was overthrown in a coup France made little pretense of opposing.</p>
        <p>It wasn't long before the new dictator, Manissara Bare, won the support of France with his pro-French policies.</p>
        <p>Most of the newspapers that haven't been driven out of business by Mr. Bare's regime express little doubt that France supported and encouraged the coup from the start.</p>
        <p>No one spending any time in France's former West African colonies could help but notice that France seems unable to accept the word ''former'' when formulating its policy toward them.</p>
        <p>France's desperate attempts to hold onto the power and prestige it once possessed as a global empire have led to policies that have done a great deal of harm to West Africa. Those policies should receive considerably more attention than they  do.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER ALBIN-LACKEY</p>
        <p>Boston, March 18, 1997</p>
      </block>
